  Volume                   = {58},

  Abstract                 = {The constancy of the genetic variance-covariance matrix (G matrix) across environments and populations has been discussed and tested empirically over the years but no consensus has so far been reached. In this paper, I present a model in which morphological traits develop hierarchically, and individuals differ in their resource allocation and acquisition patterns. If the variance in resource acquisition is many times larger than the variance in resource allocation then strong genetic correlations are expected, and with almost isometric relations among traits. As the variation in resource acquisition decreases below a certain threshold, the correlations decrease overall and the relations among traits become a function of the allocation patterns, and in particular reflecting the basal division of allocation. A strong bottleneck can break a pattern of strong genetic correlation, but this effect diminishes rapidly with increasing bottleneck size. This model helps to understand why some populations change their genetic correlations in different environments, whereas others do not, since the key factor is the relation between the variances in resource acquisition and allocation. If a change in environment does not lead to a change in this ratio, no change can be expected, whereas if the ratio is changed substantially then major changes can be expected. This model can also help to understand the constancy of morphological patterns within larger taxa as a function of constancy in resource acquisition patterns over time and environments. When this pattern breaks, for example on islands, larger changes can be expected.},
  Publisher                = {BioOne},
  Review                   = {REVIEWS OF THRY AND EXP FOR G MATRICES

This is more of a review paper that combines the Y-model of van Noordwijk and de Jong with the bifurcation trees for traits/cells in developmental biology to model genetic correlations between traits that can include morphological characters. Overall, the paper focuses on simulations and talks about their results. Some of the main conclusions have to due with the ratio of variance and allocation versus acquisition and their effects on the observed genetic correlations between traits. 

There are two key measures used in the paper: 1) the ratio of lambda_1 over lambda_2 and 2) the angle between eval_1 and the isometry vector (1,.....1). The larger the ratio, the stronger the genetic correlations since the space is basically flattened into one dimension. To measure the strength of correlations, they used the angle between eval_1 and the isometry vector. When correlations were high, the leading eigen vector is almost equal to the isometry vector, but as these correlations are broken apart, the leading eigenvector departs from isometry and the angle between eval_1 and the isometry vector increases.

A basic message from all this is that variance in allocation can basically washout the effects of allocations (functional contraints) causing positive genetic correlations. This is basically summarized in figure 6, where he shows three graphs with different angles (90 degrees = low genetic correlations low ratio of acquisition variance over allocation variance, 0-90 degrees = medium size ratio of acquisition variance to allocation variance, and 0 degrees = high genetic correlations with high ratio of acquisition variance to allocation variance).

Bottlenecks have the effect of increasing the angle between eval_1 and the isometry vector, but the amount depends on the initial variance in acquisition. The higher the variance in acquisition, the less effect the bottleneck has on the angle change, but over all, severe bottlenecks will alter the genetic correlations (see figure 5). 

One important thing to note is that here, the functional constraints again manifest through allocations that give rise to trade-offs between pairs, which is different from the way functional constraints enter charnov and charlesworth's approach using QG or optimization. There should be an equilivalence between them, but that is not explained by charlesworth in his paper. However, it might appear in the prior paper by Arnold (1992). I don't recall seeing it there, but I will check again.

Lastly, Bjorklund uses the results of his work (specifically how ratio of V_alloc / V_acqui affects genetic correlations) to suggest that the mixed results obtained from empirical studies might be due to the underlying differences in allocation.
Interestingly he points out that differences in size correspond to differences in allocation patterns. In some populations (such as in birds), V_alloc << V_acqui, meaning that selection against allocation will still produce mostly size differences (allocation), i.e overall size. The smaller V_alloc, the more rapid the divergence in non size related correlations. He discusses the patterns in Island models and how this might relate.}
