\cite{roff1999does} stated that long-term prediction of the evolution of quantitative traits is a problem because it requires genetic parameters to remain constant (i.e. constant \G matrix). He mentions that the proposition is often justified by assuming that selection is too weak to significantly erode additive genetic variances as they are restored by mutations (cites Lande 1976, 1979). Lande's justification in the 1976 paper makes the observation that in directional selection experiments on quantitative characters, $h^2$ and $\sigma^2$ remain constant even after the mean has changed a substantial amount of standard deviations (Mather and Harrison, 1949; Winter, 1929; Robertson and Reeve, 1952), so that for weaker selection typical in natural populations, an equilibrium amount of heritable variation is can be maintained by the accumulation of mutations; the weak selection assumption is not always valid (Ender 1986). \cite{roff1999does} notes that there is no theoretical justification for constant genetic architecture (turelli 1988, arnold 1992), and the question must be addressed empirically, which is what he aims to do in the remainder of the paper.}
